Wayne Community Schools Foundation
September 3 at 10:43 AM ·

For anyone looking to use the lights at Kern Track here is some information about them. The lights can be turned on using the button by the light pole (pictured) in the parking lot just north of the track. The lights can come on as early as 5 a.m. and will turn off automatically at 10 p.m. When you push the button, two lights on each pole will come on for 1 hour and it is plenty of light to be able to exercise in the morning or at night. The second picture shows a unit at the west end of the track with a light on top. That light will begin flashing when 5 minutes are left on the timer so if you want to keep exercising you will have to go push the button again.

Please congratulate these students on this fine achievement.

Dear All 5th Grade Parents/Guardians,

Our in-person beginning band rental meeting will be held at the Wayne Elementary Gym on Tuesday, August 25th, 6:30 PM. We hope to see you at the meeting! For those who prefer, it will also be simulcast on Zoom by Ray’s Midbell Music. In addition to having a team in Wayne on the 25th, they will have several dedicated staff at their store available in Zoom rooms to answer questions and process instrument rental and essential supplies purchase.

Both the Sioux City and Norfolk music stores offer online rental and have very knowledgeable staff that can assist you if you have any questions.

I hope to see you all there.

Wayne Community Schools Foundation
August 24 at 9:16 AM ·

Wayne Community Schools and the Wayne Community Schools Foundation would like to recognize its Difference Maker of the Week and will honor a district employee each week. This will be a chance for people to get to know the employees outside of work. Main Street Garage has partnered with us and is awarding each week’s Difference Maker of the Week with $25 in Chamber Bucks! This week’s Difference Maker of the Week is Judy Poehlman. Judy is the food service manager and has been with Wayne Community Schools for 37 years. Get to know Judy through the question and answer session below!

Q: Have you met any celebrities? If so, who were they?
A: Every student who walks into our kitchen at school is a celebrity!

Q: Do you have any pets? If so, what do you have?
A: A dog, Lucy.

Q: What is your favorite season?
A: All of them, I enjoy the changing of the seasons.

MEET THE NEW TEACHERS!

I am Jacob Daum and I am the new 7-12 Resource teacher. I was born and raised here in Wayne. I graduated from Wayne High School in 2016. I received my Bachelors Degree in K-12 Special Education at Wayne State College. While attending college, I worked as a paraprofessional and a coach in our school system. post_text:
MEET THE NEW TEACHERS!

Hi! My name is Mrs. Smith and I will be the 7-8th grade Science teacher this year at Wayne Community Schools.
I was born and raised in Odebolt, Iowa. I came to Nebraska to attend Wayne State College. I received a degree with a major in Elementary Education and Early Childhood, and an endorsement in coaching. I also have my Master’s degree in Curriculum and Instruction.
I met my husband while in Wayne and thought it was a great place for our family. We have two boys, Blake and Colton. We spend a lot of time traveling to visit family. We love spending time outside playing ball, swimming, golfing, gardening, or spending time at the lake! We also enjoy playing numerous card, board, or other games together. One of our latest fascinations is escape rooms!

PLEASE DO NOT APPLY FOR THIS JOB THROUGH FACEBOOK! APPLICATIONS CAN BE PICKED UP AT THE HIGH SCHOOL! Thank you!

Para Professionals

Wayne Community Schools is hiring para professional staff for both the Special Education Department and the Early Learning Center. We are looking for responsible, self motivated, and detail-oriented people who are passionate about kids. Pay will be based on experience and education. Positons are for 20-30 hours per week. Qualified candidates must have a High School Diploma and a Valid Driver’s License.
Applications are available at Wayne High School. A background check will be concluded prior to an individual being hired. Applications will be accepted until positions are filled

Send Applications to:
Misty Beair, EdS.
Special Education Director/Early Learning Center Director
Wayne Community Schools
611 West 7th St
Wayne, NE 68787
402-833-1450

Or email resume to:
mibeair1@waynebluedevils.org

Wayne Community Schools is an Equal Opportunity and Veterans Preference employer.

post_text:
This year Wayne Community Schools and the Wayne Community Schools Foundation would like to recognize its Difference Maker of the Week and will honor a district employee each week. This will be a chance for people to get to know the employees outside of work. Main Street Garage has partnered with us and is awarding each week’s Difference Maker of the Week with a $25 Amazon gift card! This week’s Difference Maker of the Week is Carrie Wendte. Carrie is a third grade teacher and has been with Wayne Community Schools for 11 years. Get to know Carrie through the question and answer session below!

Q: What makes you laugh the most?
A: My sisters

Q: Pizza or tacos?
A: Pizza

Q: What is your favorite zoo animal?
A: Giraffes

Q: If you were a super-hero, what power would you have?
A: The ability to free time

Q: What is your favorite app on your phone?
A: Instagram

Q: What was your first job?
A: Dairy Queen

Q: Where is one place you would like to visit?
A: Bali, Indonesia

Q: What skill would you like to master?
A: Speaking Spanish

post_text:
Our Wayne High Seniors will celebrate their last day of school on Friday, May 1st, by kicking off a special Cruise Main in Wayne night in their honor. The class will leave, in their vehicles, from the high school parking lot at 7:00 p.m. on May 1st. Please join the community in congratulating and cheering on these seniors who have ended their senior year like no other class at WHS. We are asking for community members to line Main Street, and anywhere along the procession route, in their vehicles to honk and cheer as the seniors pass by. Once all of the seniors have passed, community members are invited to join in a great night of cruising. Please follow social distancing guidelines.

Starting at 7:00, the procession will go east from the high school on 7th Street, turn right onto Main Street, through downtown and turn around at Victor Park to go back north.

Meal distribution changes beginning Monday:

1. We are allowing only 1 family in the school at a time. Please wait outside if you see someone already in.
2. Please stay behind the green line on the floor until your meals are brought to the table.
3. Please exit down the South hallway and exit through the South doors.

Thank you for your patience in this ever changing time we are in! We love seeing your faces but we want everyone to be safe.

Monday's meal will be chicken nuggets.

post_text:
OnToCollege with John Baylor
Juniors and Seniors-check out the OnToCollege FaceBook page.

As the coronavirus pandemic continues to make its presence known worldwide, the number of people and businesses feeling its effect continues to rise. With students being quarantined from school and the ACT and SAT cancelling their next test dates, it’s no surprise that the virus has complicated the college planning process. In this special episode of “Ask John Anything!”, John offers a few ways to relieve some of the stress brought on from coronavirus concerns, and how students can best take advantage of their newfound free time.
